Notwithstanding the alacrity of the soldiers‚ they were disposed to discuss rather than obey the commauds of their leaders (Tyler). Mallet is subj. after qui, as expressing the result (yet, so that they, &c.).—pessimum . . . fao· tum est). What they actually undertook to do was the worst which they could have done, viz. to proceed on a march of sixteen miles to take possession of the junction of the Adda and the Po (just south of the camp of the enemy, at Cremona), and this, too, heavy with baggage, and sure to be attaeked before they could reach it and encamp there, by the fresh troops of Vitellius. Notwithstanding the objections of Celsus and Paulinus, however, they were proceeding towards that point (petebant), when, by a despatch from Otho, the battle was brought on at a bridge opposite Brixellum, at an island in the Po (sec. 33-35), which, according to Heraeus, was about four miles east of the junction (i.e. towards Bedriacum).
